1. Written Advocacy

1.1. Effective Advocacy

  • Humanize your client and cause
  • Keep your arguments clear and concise
  • Use roadmaps to orient your audience
  • Be honest
  • Comply with applicable rules

1.2. Common Motions

  • Motion to Dismiss
  • Motion to Compel (Production of Discovery)
  • Motion for Judgment
    • Judgment on the Pleadings
    • Summary Judgment
    • Judgment for Acquittal
    • Judgment Nothwithstanding the Verdict
  • Motion in Limine

1.3. Motion to Dismiss

  • Typically based upon a limited set of factual allegations
  • Relief: Dismissal of the case

1.4. Discovery Motions

  • Typically based upon (1) what the party has requested and (2) what the other party has produced
  • Relief: Production of the discovery (or sanctions)

1.5. Motion for Judgment

  • Typically based on all of the relevant, available facts
  • Typically resolve factual disputes in favor of the non-moving party
  • Relief: Judgment in the moving-party’s favor

1.6. Trial Motions

  • Often based on (1) the party’s theory of the case and (2) the expected evidence
  • Relief: often admission or exclusion of evidence

2. Memoranda in Support

2.1. Anatomy of a Memorandum

  • Caption
  • Introduction
  • Background
  • Argument
  • Conclusion
  • Signature
  • Certifications

2.2. Caption

  • Court and Jurisdiction
  • Parties
  • Case Number
  • Document Title
  • Other Annotations Required by Rule

2.3. Sample Massachusetts State Court Caption

2.4. Sample Federal Court Caption

2.5. Sample New York State Court Caption

2.6. Introduction

  • (Sometimes unlabeled)
  • Identifies parties and the relief sought
  • Establishes theme

2.7. Background

  • (Sometimes labeled Statement of Facts and/or Procedural History)
  • Continues the theme established in the introduction
  • Narrates the facts
  • Uses chronological order
  • DOES NOT ARGUE (avoid legal conclusions)

2.8. Argument

  • Uses TREAT
  • Uses persuasive headings
  • Persuades using facts and law, not (just) rhetoric
  • AVOIDS HOSTILITY AND SARCASM

2.9. Conclusion

  • Concisely states the relief requested

2.10. Signature Block

2.11. Required Certifications

  • Certificates of Service
  • Word Count Certifications
  • Conferencing Certifications

the writer states the

The writer only performs

                         		The writer analyzes the 
problem well, addressing
many of the important   
facts. The writer       
compares the case law   
and the problem facts to

the analysis, but the

                         		The writer analyzes the 
problem thoroughly. The 
writer addresses all of 
the facts, organized

authority, including

The citations mostly

4.2. Document Library

4.2.1. Memorandum

To: Law Clerk
From: Iago Johnson, Partner
Subject: Forger v. Briar
Date: February 16, 2022

We are currently preparing for trial in the Forger v. Briar matter. As you may recall, our office represents Loid Forger in his wrongful death lawsuit against Yor Briar. We are attempting to prove that Yor Briar shot and killed Loid Forger’s daughter Anya Forger.

As part of our evidence, we would like to use an email that Anya Forger sent to Loid Forger on January 6, 2020, because the email identifies Yor Briar as the person who visited Anya Forger immediately before Anya Forger’s death. The email is enclosed as Exhibit A.

Please draft a memorandum in support of a motion in limine to admit the email in evidence as an excited utterance.

\clearpage

4.2.4. Affidavit of Loid Forger

\begin{centering} COMMONWEALTH OF MASSACHUSETTS \end{centering}
Suffolk, ss. \hspace{2in} Superior Court Department
    No. 2011-CV-12304
\begin{centering} LOID FORGER,\\ as the Personal Representative\\ of the Estate of ANYA FORGER,\\ \emph{Plaintiff}, v. YOR BRIAR,\\ \emph{Defendant}. \end{centering}

I, Loid Forger, state that the following is true and correct to the best of my knowledge:

  1. I am the plaintiff in the above-captioned matter. I live in Providence, Rhode Island.
  2. I am suing Yor Briar for the wrongful death of Anya Forger.
  3. Anya Forger is my adoptive daughter. Before her death, she lived at 12 Ostania Lane in Brighton, Massachusetts.
  4. Yor Briar was a friend of my daughter.
  5. Because I am hard of hearing, my daughter usually communicated with me by email.
  6. On or about January 4, 2020, my daughter emailed me to tell me that she was feeling sick. Suspecting that it could be COVID-19, I told her to call her doctor and make an appointment. She said that she would and let me know what her doctor says.
  7. She emailed me the next day to tell me that her doctor told her to go to the local clinic for a COVID-19 test. She also told me that she would be going to the clinic the next day.
  8. On the morning of January 6, 2020, my daughter emailed me again after her trip to the clinic. The email was shorter than usual, and it seemed that she had been interrupted by a knocking on her door.
  9. The January 6 email was also unusual in that my daughter usually proofreads her emails carefully. The second paragraph of the email is ungrammatical with several typos.
  10. Based on this email, I believe that Yor Briar went to my daughter’s home on the morning of January 6, 2020, shortly before my daughter’s death.

Signed under the pains and penalties of perjury this seventeenth day of October, 2021.

\underline{/s/Loid Forger}
Loid Forger

\clearpage

4.2.5. Excerpt of Transcript of Becky Blackbell’s 911 Call

2020-01-06/11:34AM
OPERATOR: 911, what is your emergency?
CALLER: I think my neighbor's just been shot.
OPERATOR: Where are you?
CALLER: 14 Ostania Lane.
OPERATOR: What happened?
CALLER: I was in the kitchen washing my dishes
  when I heard loud arguing next door.
OPERATOR: What's the address of the place next
  door?
CALLER: 12 Ostania Lane, I think. The building is
  really close-by. That's why I could hear the
  yelling. Anyway, it only went on for a few
  minutes before I heard a gunshot. Then I saw
  someone walk out my neighbor's house and up
  the street.
OPERATOR: Did you get a good look at that person?
CALLER: No, I was afraid that person would see me.
OPERATOR: What's your neighbor's name?
CALLER: Anya Forger. I hope she's okay.
OPERATOR: Stay where you are, and stay on the
  line. Police are on their way.
CALLER: Thank you.
